    "content_hash": "sha256:2aae65a93c747449c428629f7f9e830651a91cc7f203129a5b38022e30e828b3",
    "summary": "Luxor Temple is an ancient Egyptian temple complex located on the east bank of the Nile in the city of Luxor, ancient Thebes, constructed primarily during the reigns of Amenhotep III (c. 1390–1352 BC) and [[event:1807|Ramesses II]] (c. 1279–1213 BC) during the [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]]. Unlike the [[event:1885|Karnak temple complex]] to the north, which was dedicated to the state cult of Amun-Ra, Luxor Temple was specifically associated with the rejuvenation of kingship. The annual Opet Festival, in which the statue of Amun was carried in procession from Karnak to Luxor and back, was the temple's primary ritual function.\n\nThe temple's monumental entrance pylon was erected by Ramesses II and was originally flanked by six colossal statues of the pharaoh and two obelisks. One of the obelisks was given to France in 1826 and now stands in the Place de la Concorde in Paris; the other remains in situ at Luxor. The walls of the pylon are covered with reliefs depicting the [[event:1808|Battle of Kadesh]], among the most extensive battle narrative representations to survive from the ancient world.\n\nLuxor Temple was continuously occupied and modified from its New Kingdom foundations through the Ptolemaic and Roman periods. The Romans converted part of it into a military camp, and a mosque was later constructed within its precincts and remains in use today, creating a unique layered monument spanning three thousand years of continuous religious activity. The site was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site as part of Ancient Thebes with its Necropolis in 1979.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luxor_Temple",
